\title{Towards directed univalence}
\date{2026-04-04}
\meta{external}{https://github.com/samtoth/agda-synthetic-categories/pull/75}
\author{samueltoth}
\import{stt-macros}

\subtree{
\title{Summary}
\p{This PR contains a proof of directed univalence for the category
of spaces. Given the following assumptions:}

\ol{
  \li{There is a non-trivial bounded distributive lattice #{\Delta^1}}
  \li{#{\Delta^1} is a [tiny type]()}
  \li{Cubes [detect continuity]()}
  \li{#{\Delta^1} detects connectivity}
  \li{The global points of #{\Delta^1} are #{0} and #{1}}
  \li{If #{A} is [amazingly covariant](), then for all #{i : \Delta^1},
  the type #{(i = 0) \to A} is also pamazingly covariant.}
  \li{If #{A} is a family of propositions, then so is #{\sqrt[i]{A}}
  (the [dependent amazint right adjoint]()).}
}

\p{We may show that the type #{\mathcal{S}} ([which has existed in the library
for quite a while now](stt-00BD)), satisfies directed univalance, that is, the
natural map given by covariant transport is an equivalence:
##{\Hom_{\mathcal{S}}(A,B) \simeq A \to B}}

\p{Of these assumptions, the first #{5} seem essential in the proof or even
construction of #{\mathcal{S}}; however, you may notice that the later two
`\em{axioms}' seem redundant. Indeed, (6) should follow from
combination of duality, also known as Phoa's principal, and the fact that
exponentiating a covariant family by a contravariant one should give you a
covariant family. (7) should be true for any tiny type, with no
additional axioms. So in a sense these axioms represent `holes' in the proof.
These holes constitute only a minor part of the proof and so I thought it best
to merge in the proof and leave figuring out the last details to some future
work (a decision also influenced by the fact my dissertation - written as a
report on this formalisation project - is also due in very soon!)}

\p{
In this changelog entry, which might be a little longer than usual, I will try
and explain the main component that go into this proof, and highlight what made
the remaining holes challenging to fill in.
}
}

