\subtree{
\title{The proof of directed univalence}    

  \p{With a convenient interface into amazing covariance in hand, the proof
  of directed univalence is suprisingly painless. We were able to follow almost
  exactly the strategy presented in \citek{GWB2024}, where they construct an
  inverse to the canonical transport via a carefully constructed \em{glueing type}.
  To be precise, the glueing of #{\Sigma_{A\ B : \mathcal{S}} (A \to B)} is
  given by the family #{i \mapsto \Sigma_{b} (i = 0) \to \fibre{f}{b}}.
  To show this family itself lands in #{\mathcal{S}}, we may use the closure
  properties of amazing covariance:}

  \ul{
    \li{If #{A : \mathcal{S}} and #{B : A \to \mathcal{S}}, then
    #{\Sigma_{a}B(a) : \mathcal{S}}. } 
    \li{If #{A : \mathcal{S}}, then #{a =_{A} b : \mathcal{S}}}
    \li{If #{A : \mathcal{S}}, then #{(i = 0) \to A} is covariant.}
  }

  \p{There is a general strategy for these closure property that reduce the
  problem to showing the analogous closure properties for covariant families
  over #{\Delta^1}. Since these families are given by orthogonality conditions,
  we may reuse the closure properties for these that we have already established
  in the library. The third closure property here is somewhat different in that
  it asks for a property connecting between left-fibrations and right-fibrations,
  and this is one our current holes that we hope to fill in soon, the proof
  contained in \citek{GWB2024} makes implicit use of coherence that has so far
  resisted formalisation.}

  \p{The second key idea of this proof is a lemma that allows us to show an equivalence
  between families #{\Delta^1 \to \mathcal{S}} by giving a fibrewise map which
  is an equivalence on global points of #{\Delta^1} \citet{lemma 6.8}{GWB2024}.
  This lemma is where our \em{cubes detect continuity} and \em{global points of #{\Delta^1}}
  axioms are essential.}

  \p{Now that we have the directed univalence, our next immediate steps (aside
  from dealing with the pair of unfinished proofs), are to show that
  #{\mathcal{S}} is a category; that it is [simplicial](), [Segal]() and
  Rezk. In \citek{GWB2024}, an approach is suggested to use another gluing type,
  this time gluing together commuting triangles of maps. An alternative approach
  is given in the newer work \citek{GWB2026} which utilises a lemma stating that
  types are Segal if they [lift crisply]() against all spine inclusions, which
  avoids this extra gluing type. We hope to investigate this approach, as the
  formalisation may be more simple, and it should generalise nicely to the
  category of categories, the proof of which I would like to have formalised in
  this library in the future, although we are presently quite far off from it.
  }
}
